{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}} {{Infobox Website | name = Ekşi Sözlük | logo = Ekşi Sözlük logo.png | logo_size = 150px | screenshot = EksiSozlukSS.png | screenshot_size = 250px | caption = Screenshot of the main page | url = {{URL|http://www.eksisozluk.com/}} | commercial = Yes | language = [[Turkish language|Turkish]] | registration = Required | owner = Ekşi Teknoloji ve Bilişim A.Ş. | author = Sedat "ssg" Kapanoğlu | launch date = 15 February 1999 | current status = Active }}
'''Ekşi Sözlük''' ({{IPA-tr|ecˈʃi søzˈlyc}}; "Sour Dictionary") is a collaborative hypertext "[[dictionary]]" based on the concept of Web sites built up on user contribution.<ref name="HurriyetDaily news">{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/h.php?news=eksi-sozluk-a-turkish-internet-phenomenon-2006-08-14|title=Ekşi Sözlük: a Turkish Internet phenomenon|publisher=[[Turkish Daily News]]|accessdate=27 June 2007}}</ref> However, Ekşi Sözlük is not a dictionary in the strict sense; users are not required to write correct information. It is currently one of the largest online communities in [[Turkey]] with over 400,000 registered users.<ref name="Statistics">{{cite web|url=http://eksisozluk.com/istatistik|title=Stats|publisher=[[Ek$i Sözlük]]|language=Turkish|accessdate=23 June 2010}}</ref> The number of writers is about 54,000. As an online public sphere, Ekşi Sozluk is not only utilized by thousands for information sharing on various topics ranging from scientific subjects to everyday life issues, but also used as a virtual socio-political community to communicate disputed political contents and to share personal views.<ref>{{Cite thesis|degree=M.A. dissertation |title=The Internet as a participatory medium: An analysis of the Eksi Sozluk website as a public sphere |url=http://0-proquest.umi.com.library.lausys.georgetown.edu/pqdlink?did=2119575121&Fmt=2&clientId=5604&RQT=309&VName=PQD |author=Hatice Akca |year=2005 |publisher=University of South Carolina |accessdate=25 December 2011 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
The website's founder is Sedat Kapanoğlu. He founded the website for communicating with his friends in 1999 as he was inspired by ''[[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vimeo.com/16663393|title=6 Kasım Etohum Kampı Ankara - Sedat Kapanoğlu - Eksisozluk.com|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://www.etohum.com/eksisozluk-adi-nereden-cikti</ref> Ekşi Sözlük has been successful, many other websites that use this concept has emerged, like [[İTÜ Sözlük]] in Turkish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canererden.com/2011/03/10/katilimci-sozlukler-eksi-sozluk-itu-sozluk-uludag-sozluk-v-b/|title=Katılımcı Sözlükler (Ekşi Sözlük, İtü Sözlük, Uludağ Sözlük v.b) - Caner Erden|publisher=}}</ref>
Enrollment periods to the dictionary and the criteria of acceptance are changeable.<ref name="inter-disciplinary.net">http://www.inter-disciplinary.net/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/dogu-paper.pdf</ref> Ekşi Sözlük does not accept new authors regularly; there are specific times in which new authors are accepted. There is a waiting period for new members who want to become authors in which they must post at least 10 entries. All entries are inspected according to the dictionary rules and their quality, and if they are pass inspection, the new user becomes an author. However, this process might take from months to years.
Newcomer, Newcomer awaiting approval, Registered reader, Praetors, and Hacivat are some of the user roles in Eksi Sozluk.<ref name="inter-disciplinary.net"/>
Since there are no restrictions on entries, moderators and informers are responsible for catching and deleting any inappropriate entry. Informers are usually the older generation authors who report any bad content to moderators for examination. If the moderators find the entries inappropriate, they are deleted.
Site statistics<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eksisozluk.com/istatistik|title=istatistikler - ekşi sözlük|publisher=}}</ref> are updated on daily basis. There are 300 to 400 posts on average for each author. More than half of the authors are at the age of 18–25 and the number of male users is two times more than of those females.
