'''Shanqella''' ([[Ge'ez alphabet|Ge'ez]]: ሻንቅላ ''šānḳillā'' sometimes spelled '''Shankella''', '''Shangella''', '''Shánkala''', '''Shankalla''' or '''Shangalla''') is an [[exonym]] for a number of ethnic groups that today reside primarily in the westernmost part of [[Ethiopia]] near [[South Sudan]] (especially [[Benishangul-Gumuz Region]]), but are known to have also inhabited more northerly areas until the late nineteenth century.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Swainson Fisher|first1=Richard|title=The book of the world, Volume 2|date=1852|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=ik4BAAAAQAAJ&pg=622#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> A pejorative, the term was traditionally used by the local [[Afroasiatic languages|Afro-Asiatic]]-speaking populations to refer to "[[Negro]]" persons generally, particularly those from communities speaking [[Nilo-Saharan languages]]. The etymology of Shanqella is uncertain. It has been suggested that the appellation may stem from an [[Amharic language|Amharic]] epithet meaning "black". However, it is likely that the term is instead of more ancient, [[Agaw languages|Agaw]] derivation given the Agaw substratum in the Amharic language.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lipsky|first1=George Arthur|title=Ethiopia: Its People, Its Society, Its Culture, Volume 9|date=1962|publisher=Hraf Press|page=36|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=_PRyAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Smidt|2010|p=525}}

